data.value: The one-way ANOVA tests the null hypothesis that two or more groups have the same population mean.  The test is applied to samples from two or more groups, possibly with differing sizes.
The ANOVA test has important assumptions that must be satisfied in order for the associated p-value to be valid.
Each sample is from a normally distributed population.
The population standard deviations of the groups are all equal.  This    property is known as homoscedasticity.
If these assumptions are not true for a given set of data, it may still be possible to use the Kruskal-Wallis H-test (
) although with some loss of power.
